  "text": "We previously reported that mitochondria respiration/function increases upon MTCH2 deletion in HSCs and skeletal muscle cells [CITATION_1] 22 . We hypothesize that loss of MTCH2 in these cells initially results in a decrease in mitochondria respiration/function (as seen in ESCs), and the increase observed is a compensatory mechanism to correct for the defect and keep the cells alive. In the case of ESCs, we hypothesize that increasing mitochondria respiration/function may not be sufficient to enable normal embryonic development, and thus the mitochondrial defect is not corrected and the embryos eventually die at E7.5.",
